COP 3: Come on, let's get going
with these people off that line over there.

1628
01:41:57,775 --> 01:41:59,020
Come on.

1629
01:42:05,741 --> 01:42:09,359
Captain, I'm telling you,
this thing is a mess.

1630
01:42:10,287 --> 01:42:12,445
They thought this one out, soup to nuts.

1631
01:42:12,539 --> 01:42:14,081
So, lay it out for me.

1632
01:42:14,750 --> 01:42:17,323
We photograph everybody
that came out of the bank.

1633
01:42:17,419 --> 01:42:20,254
We sit them down, we question them,
we show them the photos.

1634
01:42:20,339 --> 01:42:23,873
Most of them can't point to anybody
that's guilty of anything.

1635
01:42:24,551 --> 01:42:28,002
We ask them if they could recognise
anybody who was not one of the bad guys.

1636
01:42:28,096 --> 01:42:30,718
Even if we considered someone
as a possible suspect,

1637
01:42:30,849 --> 01:42:33,554
there's one or two or three other people
that would rule them out.

1638
01:42:33,643 --> 01:42:35,019
It's like the thing never happened.

1639
01:42:35,103 --> 01:42:37,890
- What about prints?
- Everywhere. So what?

1640
01:42:38,773 --> 01:42:42,308
- All it shows is that these people were there.
- Alibis?

1641
01:42:42,402 --> 01:42:43,730
Just about everyone.

1642
01:42:43,820 --> 01:42:45,694
Even if their alibi was weak,

1643
01:42:45,780 --> 01:42:48,865
a hostage would identify them
as being one of the good guys.

1644
01:42:48,950 --> 01:42:50,492
There we are, back to square one.

1645
01:42:50,577 --> 01:42:51,656
Priors?

1646
01:42:51,745 --> 01:42:55,160
We got one employee who had
some juvie stuff. One customer had...

1647
01:42:55,248 --> 01:42:56,363
Excuse me.

1648
01:42:57,083 --> 01:42:59,752
One customer had an out-of-state warrant
for child support.

1649
01:42:59,836 --> 01:43:02,753
Another one had a couple of priors,
G.L.A. Mostly.

1650
01:43:03,590 --> 01:43:06,544
Again, same problem.
Plus, he was a fucking idiot.

1651
01:43:06,634 --> 01:43:08,674
- Bank cameras?
- Useless.

1652
01:43:08,761 --> 01:43:11,169
I'm telling you,
they thought of everything. Almost.

1653
01:43:11,264 --> 01:43:13,553
- Sounded like everything to me.
- But this.

1654
01:43:13,641 --> 01:43:16,891
We haven't found that.357
or the perp that was holding it.

1655
01:43:16,978 --> 01:43:19,683
If you did, there'd be no prints on it anyway.

1656
01:43:20,481 --> 01:43:22,023
- Bury it.
- Bury it?

1657
01:43:22,233 --> 01:43:24,558
What the fuck do you expect me to say?

1658
01:43:28,573 --> 01:43:31,988
Captain, this thing stinks to high hell.
I mean, somebody did something here.

1659
01:43:32,076 --> 01:43:33,618
You said it yourself.

1660
01:43:33,703 --> 01:43:36,276
You got no robbery. No suspects.

1661
01:43:36,831 --> 01:43:39,156
Nobody's breathing down my neck
to come up with answers.

1662
01:43:39,250 --> 01:43:41,823
I'm not gonna breathe down yours. Bury it.

1663
01:43:45,297 --> 01:43:47,124
I wasn't expecting this.

1664
01:43:47,216 --> 01:43:50,252
I promise you,
l'll find you guys more cases to solve.

1665
01:43:52,763 --> 01:43:53,842
Okay.

1666
01:43:55,599 --> 01:43:58,470
Oh, here's something
that you probably did expect.

1667
01:43:58,561 --> 01:44:02,261
- They found that missing Madrugada money.
- No shit.

1668
01:44:02,856 --> 01:44:05,063
Yes, you want to know where it was?

1669
01:44:05,150 --> 01:44:07,309
- In my bank account?
- No.

1670
01:44:07,403 --> 01:44:09,728
- My summer house in Sag Harbour?
- No.

1671
01:44:09,822 --> 01:44:11,482
- My wallet?
- No.

1672
01:44:12,408 --> 01:44:15,112
Then, no. I don't want to know.

1673
01:44:22,960 --> 01:44:24,668
MITCHELL: This is bullshit, man.

1674
01:44:24,753 --> 01:44:26,995
I mean, we're the only ones left
trying to catch the bad guys

1675
01:44:27,089 --> 01:44:28,749
and they're gonna come after us like that?

1676
01:44:28,840 --> 01:44:30,833
L'll tell you what.
Every one of your accusers, man,

1677
01:44:30,926 --> 01:44:34,342
I say we go after them all, Keith,
Michael Corleone style.

1678
01:44:34,429 --> 01:44:36,469
"Michael Corleone,
do you renounce Satan?"

1679
01:44:36,556 --> 01:44:38,134
"Yes, I renounce him."

1680
01:44:39,309 --> 01:44:41,349
FRAZIER: There's no 392.

1681
01:44:41,436 --> 01:44:44,390
- Huh?
- Safety deposit box number 392.

1682
01:44:44,481 --> 01:44:46,723
According to these records, it doesn't exist.

1683
01:44:46,816 --> 01:44:49,390
Pinstriped, mayonnaise, lying motherfucker.

1684
01:44:49,569 --> 01:44:52,772
- Didn't Coughlin say we should move on?
- Let's go.

1685
01:45:02,165 --> 01:45:04,490
Thank you, again, Your Honour.
L'll come pick it up tomorrow?

1686
01:45:04,584 --> 01:45:06,660
- Yes, you're welcome.
- Thank you.

1687
01:45:13,468 --> 01:45:14,962
What are you doing, Detective?

1688
01:45:15,053 --> 01:45:17,591
Now, what business do you have
with Judge Pasqua?

1689
01:45:17,680 --> 01:45:19,174
Police business.

1690
01:45:19,265 --> 01:45:22,634
- Weren't you told to bury this?
- I got a job to do, Miss White.

1691
01:45:22,727 --> 01:45:25,514
And since when is your job
more important than your career?

1692
01:45:25,605 --> 01:45:28,012
- Or did you forget our arrangement?
- We didn't have any arrangement.

1693
01:45:28,107 --> 01:45:29,518
Let me tell you how this works. You...

1694
01:45:29,609 --> 01:45:31,648
No, let me tell you how this works.

1695
01:45:31,736 --> 01:45:34,939
You press here to record
and you press here to play.

1696
01:45:35,031 --> 01:45:37,356
MADELEINE: (OVER RECORDER) There's
also the matter of the $140,000

1697
01:45:37,450 --> 01:45:38,612
that seems to have walked away

1698
01:45:38,701 --> 01:45:41,453
from the Madrugada cheque-cashing bust.

1699
01:45:41,621 --> 01:45:43,862
FRAZIER: I didn't have anything
to do with that, so...

1700
01:45:43,956 --> 01:45:46,032
MAYOR: We'd like to be
in your corner on that.

1701
01:45:46,125 --> 01:45:48,960
In exchange for what? I mean, what,
do you want me to do something unethical?

1702
01:45:49,045 --> 01:45:51,002
I mean, no disrespect to the both of youse

1703
01:45:51,088 --> 01:45:53,128
but I don't need you
to be in my corner, Mr Mayor.

1704
01:45:53,215 --> 01:45:54,544
Look, I'm innocent.

1705
01:45:54,633 --> 01:45:57,385
MADELEINE: Innocent or guilty,
you're still going down.

1706
01:45:58,220 --> 01:46:02,218
MAYOR: Give Miss White whatever
she needs, or your career is over.

1707
01:46:02,683 --> 01:46:03,798
Done.

1708
01:46:04,185 --> 01:46:05,383
Kaput.

1709
01:46:06,896 --> 01:46:09,850
So? You gave me what I wanted.

1710
01:46:09,940 --> 01:46:13,060
Your career is blossoming
and all is right with the world.

1711
01:46:13,152 --> 01:46:14,646
What was Case hiding?

1712
01:46:17,823 --> 01:46:21,274
You know, there's a famous saying
by the Baron de Rothschild.

1713
01:46:23,036 --> 01:46:26,240
"When there's blood on the streets,
buy property."

1714
01:46:28,709 --> 01:46:31,745
I think Mr Case
really took that sentiment to heart.

1715
01:46:31,837 --> 01:46:34,707
But he is no different
than half the Fortune 500.

1716
01:46:36,091 --> 01:46:37,834
Let it go, Detective.

1717
01:46:39,303 --> 01:46:40,927
You're a good cop.

1718
01:46:41,680 --> 01:46:43,423
This city needs you.

1719
01:47:11,584 --> 01:47:15,084
- Lady! Lady, you're in the wrong place.
- I have an appointment.

1720
01:47:23,680 --> 01:47:24,878
Arthur.

1721
01:47:25,682 --> 01:47:28,255
- Good morning.
- Miss White.

1722
01:47:29,060 --> 01:47:30,388
Have a seat.

1723
01:47:32,272 --> 01:47:35,107
Thank you, Vincent. That's all for now.
Thank you.

1724
01:47:35,608 --> 01:47:36,937
(CASE CLEARING THROAT)

1725
01:47:38,695 --> 01:47:40,901
Well. What did he say?

1726
01:47:40,988 --> 01:47:43,989
Well, Detective Frazier
turned out to be quite sharp.

1727
01:47:44,075 --> 01:47:47,241
But I just fast-tracked his career a little
and he's under control.

1728
01:47:47,328 --> 01:47:50,282
I hope so. Tell me about the envelope.

1729
01:47:50,706 --> 01:47:51,869
Where is it now?

1730
01:47:51,958 --> 01:47:54,828
Well, the gang leader
is going to hang on to it,

1731
01:47:54,919 --> 01:47:58,039
as an insurance policy
to keep you from seeking revenge.

1732
01:47:58,714 --> 01:48:01,466
Clearly, he has a very low opinion of you.

1733
01:48:01,550 --> 01:48:02,879
And what might that be?

1734
01:48:02,968 --> 01:48:06,254
Well, let's see.
In a nutshell, that you got rich,

1735
01:48:06,472 --> 01:48:09,556
doing business with the Nazis
during the Holocaust.

1736
01:48:12,812 --> 01:48:13,926
Yes.

1737
01:48:15,147 --> 01:48:18,231
It was 60 years ago.
I was young and ambitious.

1738
01:48:18,859 --> 01:48:21,646
I saw a short path to success and I took it.

1739
01:48:23,280 --> 01:48:24,822
I sold my soul.

1740
01:48:26,575 --> 01:48:29,576
And I've been trying to buy it back
ever since.

1741
01:48:29,662 --> 01:48:34,158
But you and this mystery man,
you have an understanding?

1742
01:48:34,333 --> 01:48:38,165
I think so. And he managed
to get out of there with that envelope.

1743
01:48:39,171 --> 01:48:42,504
If someday
he comes back to blackmail you, well,

1744
01:48:43,342 --> 01:48:46,046
you'll pay him. And you'll get it back.

1745
01:48:47,346 --> 01:48:49,385
- So, I guess that's it.
- I suppose so.

1746
01:48:49,473 --> 01:48:51,346
- Bullshit.
- I beg your pardon?

1747
01:48:51,433 --> 01:48:55,300
He didn't go through all that just to stick
your envelope under his mattress.

1748
01:48:55,395 --> 01:48:58,182
Look, they left money untouched, Arthur.

1749
01:48:58,273 --> 01:48:59,352
So?

1750
01:48:59,483 --> 01:49:03,860
So, he had to have walked out of there
with something else.

1751
01:49:04,863 --> 01:49:07,354
The bank says
that there was nothing missing.

1752
01:49:07,449 --> 01:49:10,022
So, there had to have been
something in that box

1753
01:49:10,118 --> 01:49:12,823
that was worth more to him
than your envelope.

1754
01:49:14,706 --> 01:49:16,699
You don't have to tell me.

1755
01:49:16,791 --> 01:49:19,365
There's only one thing it could be anyway.

1756
01:49:22,547 --> 01:49:23,710
Diamonds.

1757
01:49:24,674 --> 01:49:26,548
And then there's the ring.

1758
01:49:27,218 --> 01:49:28,629
Cartier ring.

1759
01:49:29,262 --> 01:49:32,216
It belonged to the wife of a Parisian banker.

1760
01:49:32,640 --> 01:49:35,310
Wealthy family of French Jews.

1761
01:49:35,977 --> 01:49:39,097
And when the war came along,
the ring and everything else they owned

1762
01:49:39,188 --> 01:49:44,016
was confiscated and they were shipped off
to concentration camps. None survived.

1763
01:49:46,029 --> 01:49:47,653
We were friends.

1764
01:49:48,573 --> 01:49:50,364
I could have helped them.

1765
01:49:52,285 --> 01:49:57,112
But the Nazis paid too well.

1766
01:49:59,041 --> 01:50:03,620
Can I trust that you will keep
what you've learnt

1767
01:50:03,713 --> 01:50:06,998
here today confidential?

1768
01:50:08,092 --> 01:50:10,381
Despite whatever you may think?

1769
01:50:19,478 --> 01:50:20,889
Yes, Arthur.

1770
01:50:22,857 --> 01:50:26,023
Well, I'd love to tell you
what a monster you are,

1771
01:50:26,235 --> 01:50:30,398
but I have to help bin Laden's nephew
buy a co-op on Park Avenue.

1772
01:50:34,618 --> 01:50:37,074
If that were true, you wouldn't tell me.

1773
01:50:37,371 --> 01:50:39,529
We're listing you as a reference.

1774
01:50:52,719 --> 01:50:53,917
(SIGHING)

1775
01:50:54,012 --> 01:50:56,338
My name is Dalton Russell.

1776
01:50:56,932 --> 01:50:58,759
Pay strict attention to what I say

1777
01:50:58,850 --> 01:51:02,469
because I choose my words carefully
and I never repeat myself.

1778
01:51:02,562 --> 01:51:05,267
I've told you my name. That's the "who."

1779
01:51:06,316 --> 01:51:09,981
The "where" could most readily
be described as a prison cell.

1780
01:51:10,529 --> 01:51:12,106
But there is a vast difference

1781
01:51:12,197 --> 01:51:15,696
between being stuck in a tiny cell
and being in prison.

1782
01:51:17,410 --> 01:51:19,035
The "what" is easy.

1783
01:51:20,038 --> 01:51:24,747
Recently I planned and set in motion
events to execute the perfect bank robbery.

1784
01:51:25,794 --> 01:51:27,703
That's also the "when."

1785
01:51:28,713 --> 01:51:33,091
As for the "why,"
beyond the obvious financial motivation,

1786
01:51:33,843 --> 01:51:35,587
it's exceedingly simple.

1787
01:51:36,012 --> 01:51:37,423
Because I can.

1788
01:51:38,556 --> 01:51:40,798
Which leaves us only with the "how."

1789
01:51:41,601 --> 01:51:44,637
And therein, as the Bard would tell us,

1790
01:51:45,730 --> 01:51:47,189
lies the rub.

1791
01:51:55,448 --> 01:51:56,611
(BANGING)

1792
01:52:36,405 --> 01:52:39,988
STEVE: He's gonna smell like shit.
STEVE-O: What do you expect after a week?

1793
01:52:42,369 --> 01:52:43,449
CHAIM: Yeah.

1794
01:52:43,913 --> 01:52:46,368
Why do you think I rolled down the window?

1795
01:52:49,418 --> 01:52:50,663
(CHUCKLING)

1796
01:53:06,059 --> 01:53:07,304
Oh, shit.

1797
01:53:12,774 --> 01:53:15,312
That cop, Frazier, and his partner
are walking into the bank.

1798
01:53:15,402 --> 01:53:18,687
- Are they coming for me?
- Can't say. It's just the two of them.

1799
01:53:26,329 --> 01:53:29,330
MAN: Yeah, everything's going great today.
No.

1800
01:53:29,666 --> 01:53:32,667
Yeah, about 5:30. Okay.

1801
01:53:33,128 --> 01:53:35,666
Sounds like fun. Okay.

1802
01:53:36,464 --> 01:53:38,007
Talk to you later.

1803
01:53:59,404 --> 01:54:01,147
- Sorry.
- Excuse me.

1804
01:54:04,450 --> 01:54:05,861
Mr Hammond?

1805
01:54:05,952 --> 01:54:07,695
Good morning, Detectives.

1806
01:54:11,249 --> 01:54:12,826
Just like he planned.

1807
01:54:12,917 --> 01:54:15,490
I got a court order here
to open a safe deposit box.

1808
01:54:15,586 --> 01:54:17,496
Number 392.

1809
01:54:25,680 --> 01:54:26,759
(STEVE-O SIGHING)

1810
01:54:28,724 --> 01:54:30,468
STEVE-O: Oh, thank God.

1811
01:54:36,232 --> 01:54:37,607
Where is it?

1812
01:54:38,401 --> 01:54:39,859
I left it in there.

1813
01:54:39,944 --> 01:54:41,604
This way, Detectives.

1814
01:54:41,695 --> 01:54:44,269
Why did you do that? You left the ring.

1815
01:54:44,365 --> 01:54:45,610
Trust me.

1816
01:54:46,575 --> 01:54:48,235
I left it in good hands.

1817
01:54:49,119 --> 01:54:50,744
DALTON: I'm no martyr.

1818
01:54:51,455 --> 01:54:53,163
I did it for the money.

1819
01:54:54,875 --> 01:54:58,540
But it's not worth much
if you can't face yourself in the mirror.

1820
01:54:59,338 --> 01:55:01,959
Respect is the ultimate currency.

1821
01:55:04,802 --> 01:55:08,751
I was stealing from a man
who traded his away for a few dollars.

1822
01:55:10,641 --> 01:55:13,132
And then he tried to wash away his guilt.

1823
01:55:14,269 --> 01:55:18,314
Drown it in a lifetime of good deeds
and a sea of respectability.

1824
01:55:19,107 --> 01:55:21,230
- Let me get that.
- Let me.

1825
01:55:21,318 --> 01:55:22,693
It almost worked, too.

1826
01:55:22,778 --> 01:55:23,892
Okay.

1827
01:55:25,989 --> 01:55:27,365
But inevitably,

1828
01:55:28,325 --> 01:55:30,483
the further you run from your sins,

1829
01:55:31,328 --> 01:55:34,412
the more exhausted you are
when they catch up to you.

1830
01:55:34,623 --> 01:55:35,785
And they do.

1831
01:55:37,667 --> 01:55:39,210
Son of a bitch.

1832
01:55:39,294 --> 01:55:40,492
Certain.

1833
01:55:41,505 --> 01:55:43,165
It will not fail.

1834
01:55:47,552 --> 01:55:49,545
FRAZIER: What do you think that's worth?

1835
01:55:49,846 --> 01:55:52,515
(CHUCKLING) If you got to ask, man,
you can't afford it.

1836
01:55:52,599 --> 01:55:54,971
Thank goodness my girlfriend ain't here.

1837
01:55:57,103 --> 01:55:58,847
"Follow the ring"?

1838
01:56:12,911 --> 01:56:15,865
- Detective Frazier.
- Mr Case.

1839
01:56:16,039 --> 01:56:18,031
- How are you?
- I am great.

1840
01:56:18,458 --> 01:56:21,874
Nobody got killed at the bank.
Everybody's happy. My kind of day.

1841
01:56:21,961 --> 01:56:23,918
That's wonderful. Wonderful.

1842
01:56:24,005 --> 01:56:25,713
- Detective Mitchell.
- Mr Case.

1843
01:56:25,798 --> 01:56:27,755
- Be seated, gentlemen.
- Thank you.

1844
01:56:27,842 --> 01:56:30,131
- Can I offer you anything?
- No.

1845
01:56:30,219 --> 01:56:31,797
I must say

1846
01:56:32,180 --> 01:56:34,587
I was most impressed

1847
01:56:35,766 --> 01:56:37,676
by the way you handled that business.

1848
01:56:37,768 --> 01:56:39,049
Thank you, Mr Case.

1849
01:56:39,145 --> 01:56:41,054
Whenever I hear the term
"New York's Finest"

1850
01:56:41,147 --> 01:56:42,890
you're who I think of.

1851
01:56:42,982 --> 01:56:46,232
You keep the rest of us safe
and make it look easy.

1852
01:56:48,529 --> 01:56:50,901
- Pardon me.
- Well, what's so amusing?

1853
01:56:50,990 --> 01:56:53,907
When you say "the rest of us," Mr Case,
I mean, you got to look around.

1854
01:56:53,993 --> 01:56:58,073
"The rest of us" is a category
that you haven't qualified for in a long time.

1855
01:56:58,164 --> 01:57:00,868
Touch, Detective.
I won't deny it. I've done well.

1856
01:57:00,958 --> 01:57:03,081
Yes, you have. But I'm very confused.

1857
01:57:03,169 --> 01:57:04,912
You see, I got a case

1858
01:57:05,671 --> 01:57:08,625
where armed robbers
laid siege to your bank.

1859
01:57:08,716 --> 01:57:10,044
It is your bank, right?

1860
01:57:10,134 --> 01:57:12,007
Well, I'm Chairman of the Board of Directors.

1861
01:57:12,094 --> 01:57:13,754
Then ita-zita-vene-gazoo.

1862
01:57:13,846 --> 01:57:15,755
The robbers disappear. Poof.

1863
01:57:16,098 --> 01:57:17,509
And they don't take a nickel, right?

1864
01:57:17,599 --> 01:57:19,925
- You're asking me?
- Yes, I'm asking you.

1865
01:57:20,018 --> 01:57:22,177
I mean, it's your bank. You own it.
